    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3450578043" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3450578043" />
    <a title="Merphy Napier" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41973734-merphy-napier"><img alt="Merphy Napier" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524921716p2/41973734.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3450578043?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Merphy Napier" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Merphy Napier" href="/user/show/41973734-merphy-napier">Merphy Napier</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41973734-merphy-napier?shelf=adult">adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41973734-merphy-napier?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41973734-merphy-napier?shelf=two-stars">two-stars</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3450578043" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer74540022788204266">I&apos;ll start off by saying this isn&apos;t a bad book so I don&apos;t want to discourage people from reading it. It just did so many things that I didn&apos;t like. <br/><br/>What I did like:<br/>- The writing is beautiful. Zevin had thoughtful prose and she had that slow, personal pacing that my favorite author, Fredrick Backmen has in his books. <br/>- The characters were easy to fall in love with from the start, despite their (intentional) flaws. Getting invested in these characters and their stories was not difficult for me at </span>
  <span id="freeText74540022788204266" style="display:none">I'll start off by saying this isn't a bad book so I don't want to discourage people from reading it. It just did so many things that I didn't like. <br /><br />What I did like:<br />- The writing is beautiful. Zevin had thoughtful prose and she had that slow, personal pacing that my favorite author, Fredrick Backmen has in his books. <br />- The characters were easy to fall in love with from the start, despite their (intentional) flaws. Getting invested in these characters and their stories was not difficult for me at all.<br />- The last page. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ the fact that it ends by saying the same thing that was in the beginning, "the book seller won't take what he can't sell" and then we walk in to that last line, showing us that his friend took over this bookstore. That was beautiful  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />What I didn't like:<br /><br />Unfortunately, the at the halfway point things started going downhill for me. I'll start with a nitpick and work my way down.<br /><br />- rushed moments. This was actually in the first half. Stuff like <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ The officer agreeing to let Fikry take the two year old home with him and it's all just accepted and brushed over. So the officer didn't call any families that would be more equipped? No paperwork was filled out? He didn't even care that Fikry is driving this two year old around without a carseat????? No carseat is fine with him?! I went back and double checked, none was ever mentioned when he was driving or when she was left in his store. This could have been easily resolved if it were just written out rather than rushing through it. Same with the adoption. Just a couple of really quick lines like, "There were a few things counting against me, but it worked out. The adoption took the normal amount of time." then goes on to say it took less than a year. As someone currently going through the adoption process, no, it doesn't take under a year. The "normal amount of time" is closer to 2-4 years (even several years ago when this was set). I would have loved a bit of a look into the adoption rather than just rushing through it. Again, it's a nit pic, but there are several more scenes I could write here that were just rushed through or brushed over and I felt it took authenticity from the experience.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br />- Tonal shift. At about the halfway point, we move on from a story about a grump of a man who is figuring out how to raise his new daughter (which was really sweet), to a grump of a man trying to win over the woman he's falling for. It's fine, I get that some people will like this section, I just didn't like the shift.<br /><br />Now we get to the part that I really hated. And that's the last quarter of the book.<br /><br />- The twist (for lack of better word) <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Cancer. Why does it ALWAYS have to be Cancer? I knew this was coming back because he had that strong reaction to the book about Cancer, then very shortly after, he stated that he believes in the principal of Chekhov's gun, so I knew the gun had to come back in act three. But I really hated how it came back. I thought a lot about this. Why can authors like Backmen write about topics very personal and painful to me and I feel seen, but other authors write it and I feel like it was used as a cheep device and it makes me mad? I think the reason is that some authors (like Backmen) write it in a raw and emotional way where we dig deep into the realities of it together, where as others feel like "They have Cancer. Now they're dead. Now cry. End book." When there's little exploration of the emotions and the reality of it and it's just a quick reveal, followed by an emotional scene, then end... ug. I get what the author was trying to do, but I don't think it was done well. It was a "hit 'em with emotion and leave 'em" and I just really don't like that.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br />- the plot device. It was so convoluted and ridiculous and what was the point in the end? <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ The book. I knew this had to come back eventually too. Of course it did. But when we get to how it comes back and the explanation, it was so convoluted! I mean, "I stole the book then gave it to this person to pay them off, then she came back two years later and said she couldn't sell it so she just gave it back to me, so I just put it in my closet for years, then this guy came over for the first time and saw it and knew what it was but didn't say anything, then years later after we were married, when it was needed the most, he confronted me and THEN we gave it back to him in a way so he would never find out who stole it from him in the first place." So, Fikry needed a surgery he couldn't afford to give him a couple more years to live, and now that Fikry has the book back, he can sell it and afford the surgery. Yay! He gets a few more years to live! So we just jumped through a bunch of hoops to makes sense of this book ring-a-round so we can go through this whole story, *only to skip that part of his life*. No joke, we went through all that to give Fikry a couple more years to live, then we skip over those extra years and get right to his death. Only adding to how this felt like a gimmick to me, not an exploration of a deep topic. We're not focused on his life anymore, the extra life we went through all that to get, we don't even see. Skip straight to the death and end book. So what was the point of the book plot of it doesn't even effect how we get the story?  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Again, a lot of people love this book, and I get it. It's well written and it's an emotional book. For me, I felt like I get what the author was trying to do, but I didn't like her execution of it at all. I'm gonna go read "A Man Called Ove" to make myself feel better.</span>
  <a data-text-id="74540022788204266" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


