    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1273065065" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1273065065" />
    <a title="Dolors" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18383778-dolors"><img alt="Dolors" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1629796436p2/18383778.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1273065065?book_show_action=true">Mar 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dolors" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dolors" href="/user/show/18383778-dolors">Dolors</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/21445677-the-storied-life-of-a-j-fikry">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Book lovers of all ages and literary tastes</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Dolors by: </span>
      Zevin
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18383778-dolors?shelf=read-in-2019">read-in-2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1273065065" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1898358047835969621">I don’t know how many times my eyes skimmed through this title in the last years, reminding me vaguely of how much I loved <i>Margarettown</i> in what seems like a lifetime ago, and how easily I discarded it, thinking I wouldn’t find it worthy after the more literary works I’ve come to read since I joined GR.<br/>How arrogant of me.<br/><br/>This is a simple book to read. A page turner with short chapters, written in a fast, light-hearted prose that sounds so natural and easy-going that you’ll forget you are reading </span>
  <span id="freeText1898358047835969621" style="display:none">I don’t know how many times my eyes skimmed through this title in the last years, reminding me vaguely of how much I loved <i>Margarettown</i> in what seems like a lifetime ago, and how easily I discarded it, thinking I wouldn’t find it worthy after the more literary works I’ve come to read since I joined GR.<br />How arrogant of me.<br /><br />This is a simple book to read. A page turner with short chapters, written in a fast, light-hearted prose that sounds so natural and easy-going that you’ll forget you are reading a book. Instead, you’ll feel like you are sharing cozy conversation with an old friend who is a book nerd like you.<br />And yes, you guessed it just right. <br />The novel is full of cliches. <br />A quaint bookstore located in a small island near the cost of Maine.<br />Plenty of quoted authors and works that will bring you delightful memories and spontaneous smiles.<br />A curmudgeon bookseller who lost his wife in a car accident.<br />A publishing sales rep with good reading tastes and a disastrous love life.<br />A cad disguised as a writer with a single book to prove for his talent.<br />A baby girl who offers a second chance to the young widower and brings life back to the island’s bookstore and its inhabitants.<br />But who cares about cliches when a story tugs at one’s heartstrings and sings a full symphony, with pauses and silences between powerful movements? <br />Particularly if love and only love is the dominant tune of this moving story.<br />Love of words, love of books, love of literature, love of people, love of improbable dreams… And ultimately, love of life.<br /><br />I will save you the rave I could come up with quite promptly as I just turned the last page of this heart-warming novel and my heart is overbrimming with ache and tenderness for its characters. I wasn’t expecting such an intense ending but it culminated what had been an increasingly gratifying read.<br />I will just say that I connected to this endearing story in multiple levels and that any person who loves literature will be touched by Zevin’s passion for books and by her frank eagerness to connect with those at the other side of the page. <br />What a rare gift, to be reminded of the reasons why I fell in love with books in the first place and of the importance of spreading this love like gospel. <br />Ride on, Zevin, ride on.<br /><br /><i>“We aren’t the things we collect, acquire, read. We are, for as long as we are here, only love. The things we loved. The people we loved. And these, I think these really do live on.” </i></span>
  <a data-text-id="1898358047835969621" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


