<span id="freeTextContainer11048782341723981987">Add this to my list of unpopular opinions, I guess. This is complete and utter emotional manipulation disguised as a story.<br/><br/>I debated including this, but <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[ HOW is this acceptable:<br/><blockquote>He kisses her and then she reaches under his hospital gown between his legs and squeezes. &quot;I love having sex with you,&quot; she says. &quot;If you&apos;re a vegetable when this is done, can I still have sex with you?&quot; she asks.<br/><br/>&quot;Sure,&quot; A.J. says.</blockquote><br/>So she&apos;s asking for permission to rape him. That&apos;s romantic and tear-jerking.</span></span>
  <span id="freeText11048782341723981987" style="display:none">Add this to my list of unpopular opinions, I guess. This is complete and utter emotional manipulation disguised as a story.<br /><br />I debated including this, but <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ HOW is this acceptable:<br /><blockquote>He kisses her and then she reaches under his hospital gown between his legs and squeezes. "I love having sex with you," she says. "If you're a vegetable when this is done, can I still have sex with you?" she asks.<br /><br />"Sure," A.J. says.</blockquote><br />So she's asking for permission to rape him. That's romantic and tear-jerking...how? All of these five star ratings have me very confused. If a book makes someone cry, it seems to automatically earn a high rating on this website and I will never understand that. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
